\section*{Getting Started: Style Files, and Optional Style Files}

These are the files that are part of the book macro package, 
with a description of their use:

\vskip1pt\noindent
\hbox to1in{%
{\tt kluwerbk.sty}\hfill}
\qquad The basic set of macros for technical book style.

\vskip1pt\noindent
\hbox to1in{%
{\tt psfonts.sty}\hfill}
\qquad Optional style file if you want to 
use PostScript fonts.

\vskip1pt\noindent
\hbox to1in{%
{\tt dblspace.sty}\hfill}
\qquad Optional style file to make your text double
spaced for easier proofing.

\vskip1pt\noindent
\hbox to1in{%
{\tt booksamp.tex}\hfill}
\qquad A sample file showing the macros in use.

\vskip1pt\noindent
\hbox to1in{%
{\tt booksamp.srt}\hfill}
\qquad The sorted index file to be used when 
\LaTeX\ is run on booksamp.tex.



\subsection*{The Basic Style}

The basic documentstyle for Kluwer books is `kluwerbk'. 

\verb+\documentstyle{kluwerbk}+

\subsection*{Font style files}
The default font selection will be Computer Modern, but
the user can choose to use PostScript fonts, which will give
the book a more finished look. Your choice should be determined
by which fonts you have available on your system. Most likely the final
version of your book will be produced using PostScript fonts but in the
earlier versions it is fine to print your book using Computer Modern fonts.

There is no difference in the use of the macros in 
whether or not you use PostScript. You may notice that
the command \verb+\bit+ which will produce bold italics
with the PostScript font file, but will produce Computer Modern bold when 
the cmfonts file is used.

The optional style file
`{\tt[psfonts]}' is used for PostScript font declarations, used like this:

\verb+\documentstyle[psfonts]{kluwerbk}+

\vtop to0pt{
\subsubsection*{Changes in the psfonts.sty file}
If you do use PostScript fonts, you may need to make changes in 
the psfonts.sty
file to make the PostScript font name match the names available on
your system. The PostScript names vary according to what driver
program (dvips, dvi2ps, dvipsone, etc.) you use to translate
your .dvi file into PostScript to appear on your printer. The naming
conventions used here are those used by the Arbortext dvips driver.

There are comments in the psfonts.sty file to show you where to make
the changes, and what the Adobe font names are for each font named.
\vss}
\newpage

If you look in your directory where the .tfm files are stored, you
can find the names of your PostScript fonts. Then you can
change the psfonts.sty file, as in the following examples.


Part of the original file:

\code
\begin{verbatim}
...
%% Times-Roman
\def\timesroman{psmtimr }

%% Times-Bold
\def\timesbold{psmtimb }
...
\end{verbatim}
\endcode

Changed version, using the Y\&Y font names:

\code
\begin{verbatim}
...
%% Times-Roman
\def\timesroman{tirx }

%% Times-Bold
\def\timesbold{tibx }
...
\end{verbatim}
\endcode



\subsection*{Double Space Option}
You may also use the {\tt dblspace} option to increase the vertical 
distance between lines in your text, to make an easy to
read draft version of your article. Use one of the following
documentstyle declarations:

\begin{verbatim}
\documentstyle[psfonts,dblspace]{kluwerbk}
\documentstyle[dblspace]{kluwerbk}
\end{verbatim}


\subsection*{Edited book style}
To make an edited book for Kluwer, you must use the
optional style file, editedbk.sty, i.e.,

\begin{verbatim}
\documentstyle[psfonts,editedbk]{kluwerbk}
\end{verbatim}

{\bf Please see the documentation that is written specifically for
edited books:\hfill\break editedbk.doc.}

\subsection*{New Use for Double Backslashes}
Double backslashes maybe used to start a new line in the
title, chapter title, author names, appendix title, and section heads.

For instance:\verb+\section{This is a\\ Test Section Head}+

\t
\vskip-12pt
\vskip1sp
\section{This is a\\ Test Section Head}
\endt


\newpage

\section*{Front Matter Commands}
This section shows the beginning commands in the preparation of your book.
A full sample is found on the next section `Sample Front Matter'.

The user should enter the following commands underneath
the \verb+\begin{document}+ command:

\begin{verbatim}
\title{(Title of Book)}
\end{verbatim}
Double backslashes may be used to arrange the lines in the
book title on the title page.

\begin{verbatim}
\author{(First LAST)}
\affil{(Author affiliation)}
\location{(Author location)}
\end{verbatim}

This set of three commands should be used for each author.
All three are needed for correct macro functioning.
Note that the author's last name should be entered in all caps.

If you want to have several authors, with a single affiliation,
you may separate authors with a double backslash.

\begin{verbatim}
\author{Carolyn SMYTHE\\ George SANTAYANA}
\affil{Cambridge University}
\location{Cambridge, UK}
\end{verbatim}

If you have a number of authors with separate affiliations, 
enter a new group of 

\verb+\author \affil \location+  

as you see on the sample page.

\begin{verbatim}
\author{Second AUTHOR}
\affil{Second Affiliation}
\location{Second Location}
\end{verbatim}


\subsubsection{Title page and Author title page}

After the above commands are entered, the title page and author title page
commands may be used:

\begin{verbatim}
\titlepage
\authortitlepage
\end{verbatim}

\vtop to0pt{
\verb+\title+, \verb+\author+, \verb+\affil+, and \verb+\location+ 
should all be entered before
using the commands \verb+\titlepage+ and \verb+\authortitlepage+.
\vss}

\newpage
\subsubsection{Table of Contents, List of Figures and List of Tables}
Table of contents, LOF, and LOT are produced the same way with this
package as they are with standard \LaTeX. 

\begin{verbatim}
\tableofcontents
\listoffigures
\listoftables
\end{verbatim}

List of figures and list of tables are at the author's option.
You may find it necessary to edit the *.lot or *.lof file in 
the following case. If you have a chapter that does not include
any figures or tables, you may want to remove the chapter
call from the .lof or .lot file, i.e.,

\begin{verbatim}
\contentsline {listenv}{{\pbf Chapter\ 3}}{33}
\end{verbatim}
\vskip-12pt
\noindent for instance, if there are no figures found in that 
chapter.

\subsubsection{Preface}
Making the preface is done with \verb+\preface Here is your preface...+.

