\section*{Part, Chapter and Section Heads}
The command for making a part or chapter is not changed from
ordinary \LaTeX\ 

\noindent
\verb+\part{Your Part Title}+.
\verb+\chapter{Your Chapter Title}+.

\noindent
Remember that you may use double backslashes if you want
to specify when a new line starts in the chapter title.

\subsection*{Shortened Version of Chapter Title}
You may need a shortened version of your chapter title so
that it will fit in the running head. This is how to do it:

\verb+\chapter{Here is an Extremely\\ Verbose Chapter Title}+

\verb+\chaptermark{Shortened Title for Running Heads}+

\subsection*{Section Heads}
There is little that needs be said about section heads except
that you can break lines with the double backslash, and
that they should be entered using upper case for the
first letter of important words and lower case for the rest.
Even though the section heads appear in the text with all
caps, the upper and lower case is necessary when the section head
appears in the table of
contents.

\vtop to 0pt{
\code
\begin{verbatim}
\section{This is a Section}
\subsection{This is a Subsection Head}
\subsubsection{This is a Subsubsection Head}
\end{verbatim}
\endcode
\t
\section{This is a Section}
\subsection{This is a Subsection Head}
\subsubsection{This is a Subsubsection Head}
\endt
\vss}


