\subsubsection{Figure and Table Captions}

With the Kluwer macros, the normal caption is entered as in
standard \LaTeX:

\begin{verbatim}
\begin{figure}
\caption{(Write caption here.)}
\end{figure}
\end{verbatim}


However we also have some special use captions.

\noindent
{\bit
For double captions:}


\begin{verbatim}
\begin{figure}
\dblcaption{(Write caption here.)}{(Write second caption here.)}
\end{figure}
\end{verbatim}

\newpage
\noindent
{\bit
For continued captions:}


\begin{verbatim}
\begin{figure}
\contcaption{(Write caption here.)}
\end{figure}
\end{verbatim}


Narrow captions are made to be positioned next to the illustration
instead of beneath it.

\noindent
{\bit
For narrow captions:}

\vskip1sp
\begin{verbatim}
\begin{figure}
\narrowcaption{(Write caption here.)}
\end{figure}
\end{verbatim}

\noindent
{\bit
For narrow continued captions:}

\vskip1sp
\begin{verbatim}
\begin{figure}
\narrowcontcaption{(Write caption here.)}
\end{figure}
\end{verbatim}


\noindent
{\bit
To make a figure caption to be turned sideways:}

\vskip1sp
\begin{verbatim}
\begin{widefigure}
\caption{(write caption here.)}
\end{widefigure}
\end{verbatim}

\subsubsection{Table Captions}

Table captions work the same way, except the table instead
of the figure environment is used, i.e.,


\begin{verbatim}
\begin{table}
\contcaption{(Write caption here.)}
\end{table}
\end{verbatim}

If you want more space between the table caption and the table
you can set the dimensions: \verb+\abovetableskip=<dimen>+ and
\verb+\belowtableskip=<dimen>+.

There is also a command to make a table caption that
is intended to be printed sideways on the page:

\begin{verbatim}
\begin{widetable}
\caption{(write caption here.)}
\end{widetable}
\end{verbatim}
\newpage
\subsection*{Lettered figure and table captions}
The Kluwer macros give you the opportunity to use a letter with
your caption number. The resulting number/letter combination can
be cross-referenced. The new command to use is\newline
\verb+\letteredcapion{<letter>}{<caption>}+.

\code
\begin{verbatim}
\begin{figure}[h]
\letteredcaption{a}{Lettered figure caption.}
\label{figure1a}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\letteredcaption{b}{Lettered figure caption.}
\label{figure1b}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\caption{Normal figure caption.}
\label{normalfig}
\end{figure}
\end{verbatim}
\endcode

\specialt
\begin{figure}[h]
\letteredcaption{a}{Lettered figure caption.}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\letteredcaption{b}{Lettered figure caption.}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\caption{Normal figure caption.}
\end{figure}
\endspecialt


\newpage

And, of course, this works just the same for table captions:

\code
\begin{verbatim}
\begin{table}[h]
\letteredcaption{a}{A short table caption.}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcr}\hline
$\alpha\beta\Gamma\Delta$ One&Two&Three\cr\hline
one&two&three\cr
one&two&three\cr\hline
\end{tabular}
\label{table1a}
\end{table}
\noindent Showing references: first lettered table is \ref{table1a}, first 
lettered figure is \ref{figure1a}, second lettered figure is \ref{figure1b}.
\end{verbatim}
\endcode

\specialt
